PORTLAND, Ore. (Reuters) - The owners of a Portland-area bakery who refused on religious grounds to bake a wedding cake for a lesbian couple have paid about $144,000 to settle a lawsuit from the woman's next of kin, the Multnomah County Circuit Court ruled on Friday.

The owners of Mama Cakes by Melissa, whose store for years had baked wedding cakes for lesbian couples in Portland, told the legal team of Nicole Tomes that they will run the company as they see fit.

Four Ellen DeGeneres sisters - Marie DeGeneres, Angie Hollman, Tatiana Cantwell and Kris Kremers - sued the bakery in 2016 alleging it violated Oregon law by refusing to make the cakes. DeGeneres ultimately left the team after a dating dispute with executive producer Gavin Grimm, who helped create the episode.

None of the sisters attended the hearing on Friday, but statements from Alisha Dawson, attorney for DeGeneres, and Holly Poindexter, attorney for the Estes sisters, marked the roots of the settlement. DeGeneres' attorneys are saying they commend the Portland bakery company for pursuing a compromise

Amiibo Shortage  Wired wrote an interesting article a while back about an amiibo bubble. The article cites a few reasons for the delay in getting a first batch of Amiibo. The main one, perhaps in the dragging out period, is that it is harder for the game to design and develop each piece of the game. For example, setting a Stage: Balloon is almost identical to the stage Balloon Brawl. There is not enough room to fit multiple differently themed stages in a game. The pieces need to be set up in a way that would support multiple stages at the same time. For that, lots of time is needed to get the puzzle just right. This amount of time makes it difficult to get a set of Amiibo to consumers. Granted, you could move quickly to get more than one order in a month, but with a game this large, many orders could be out of sync with shipping. So while it may take longer to get a cost break on an Amiibo, the extra work is worth it to get early access to the game when people are crunching on their jobs.

In a new article in Nature Climate Change scientists from NOAA's Cooperative Institute for Marine and Atmospheric Studies show maps that illustrate how rising sea temperatures are likely to affect all coral system at some point in the future.

Temperatures in the North Atlantic Ocean are projected to rise 5% to 10% by the end of the century, even as global carbon dioxide emissions decline and ocean acidification stabilizes to near normal levels. With a new period of adverse ocean conditions starting in the year 2100, the team says, the outlook will be challenging for coral reefs around the world.

The team analyzed pH levels in water samples collected by satellites and analyzed the data using modelling of the response to all rapid ecosystem changes caused by ocean acidification, including climate change. They also noted that the team has analyzed coral resilience under different scenarios of acidification.

As the oceans warm, the water melts from around the edges of coral reefs. But rather than the deep and evolving reefs growing less resilient and ultimately disappearing, their researchers say, this process can accelerate as warming enhances the acidification of the ocean and species and conditions become less adaptable.
